2. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

We will analyze the data by summarizing its main characteristics using visual methods.

The dataset contains \(41,188\) examples, \(20\) features and a response variable labled by y indicating if the client subscribes a bank term deposit (“yes” or “no”), ordered by date (from May 2008 to November 2010).

D = read.table("bank-additional-full.csv", header=TRUE, sep=";")

The data is imbalanced.

ggplot(D, aes(y)) + geom_bar() + 
  ggtitle(paste("Distribution of y with the imbalanced ratio", round(sum(table(D$y)[2])/sum(table(D$y)), 2)))

The following function is to calculate the ratio of clients who subscribe the product for a categorical feature within each level.

findRatio = function(featureName) {
  mat = matrix(0, nrow = length(unique(D[,featureName])), ncol = 4)
  for (x in unique(D[,featureName])) {
    mat[which(unique(D[,featureName])==x),] = c(x, sum(D$y=="yes" & D[,featureName]==x), sum(D$y=="no" & D[,featureName]==x), sum(D$y=="yes" & D[,featureName]==x) / sum(D[,featureName]==x))
    }
  df = data.frame(mat, stringsAsFactors = F)
  colnames(df) = c(featureName, "yes", "no", "ratio")
  df$yes = as.numeric(df$yes)
  df$no = as.numeric(df$no)
  df$ratio = as.numeric(df$ratio)
  df$ratio = round(df$ratio, 2)
  df
  }

2.1.1. age

The feature age is the age of client (numeric). It has no relationship with y.

2.1.2. job

The feature job is type of job (categorical). For subscribed ratio, the top 3 categories are student, retired and unemployed, while the last 3 categories are entrepreneur, services and blue-collar. Since there are variations between subscribed ratio within each category, it has a relationship with y.

table(D$job)

       admin.   blue-collar  entrepreneur     housemaid    management       retired self-employed      services       student 
        10422          9254          1456          1060          2924          1720          1421          3969           875 
   technician    unemployed       unknown 
         6743          1014           330 
jobRatio = findRatio("job")
ggplot(jobRatio, aes(x=reorder(job, -ratio), y=ratio)) + geom_bar(stat="identity") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=45, hjust=1)) +
  xlab("job") + ggtitle("Ranking subscribed ratio within each category of job")

ggplot(merge(D,jobRatio), aes(x=reorder(job,-ratio), fill=y)) + geom_bar() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=45, hjust=1)) +
  annotate("text", x = 1:12, y=11000, label = sort(jobRatio$ratio, decreasing = T)) +
  xlab("job") + ggtitle("job VS y")

3. Insights

Clients who are student or illiterate are likely to subscribe (\(27\%\) chance to subscribe), while those who are blue-collar or with elementary/middle school diploma are unlikely to do so (\(8\%\) chance to subscribe).

Clients who had a contact in March, Dec, Sep or Oct are likely to subscribe (\(47\%\) chance to subscribe), while those who had contacted in May are unlikely to do so (\(6\%\) chance to subscribe).

Clients who had a 7 mins or more duration contact are to subscribe (\(40\%\) chance to subscribe), while clients are to subscribe (\(2\%\) chance to subscribe) if the contact duration is less than 2 mins.

Clients who had bought the product from the previous marketing campaign are likely to subscribe again (\(65\%\) chance to subscribe), while those who are new or didn’t subscribe previously are unlikely to do so (\(9\%\) chance to subscribe).

Clients are likely to subscribe when economic is not good, i.e., the number of employees is lower than 5100 (\(24\%\) chance to subscribe), while clients are unlikely to subscribe when the number of employees is higher than 5200 (\(6\%\) chance to subscribe).
